{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13853"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13853"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.13,0.24,0.1,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54578"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13853"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40090"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"6125"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54578"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after falling onto her outstretched left hand. She has swelling around her left elbow but is otherwise clinically well. Her medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. She has no previous orthopaedic surgical history. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her left elbow is slightly flexed with swelling around the joint. The neurovascular status of her left upper limb is intact. A left elbow X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the \u0027terrible triad\u0027 in elbow dislocation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior elbow dislocation, radial head and olecranon fracture","Anterior elbow dislocation, radial head and coronoid process fracture","Posterior elbow dislocation, radial head and olecranon fracture","Posterior elbow dislocation, radial notch and coronoid process fracture","Posterior elbow dislocation, radial head and coronoid process fracture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u0027terrible triad\u0027 of the elbow is a severe injury pattern that consists of three components: \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior elbow dislocation, radial head fracture, and coronoid process fracture\u003C/strong\u003E. This combination of injuries results in significant elbow instability and can be challenging to manage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior elbow dislocation, radial head and olecranon fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct description of the terrible triad. Anterior elbow dislocations are much less common than posterior dislocations, and the olecranon is not typically involved in the terrible triad injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior elbow dislocation, radial head and coronoid process fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect. While it includes two components of the terrible triad (radial head and coronoid process fractures), the dislocation in the terrible triad is posterior, not anterior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior elbow dislocation, radial head and olecranon fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is close but not correct. The terrible triad involves the coronoid process, not the olecranon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior elbow dislocation, radial notch and coronoid process fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the radial head, not the radial notch, is involved in the terrible triad.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe terrible triad injury typically occurs when a patient falls on an outstretched hand, as in this case. The force transmitted through the arm causes the elbow to dislocate posteriorly, often resulting in associated fractures of the radial head and coronoid process. This injury pattern is called \u0027terrible\u0027 because it often leads to persistent instability, arthritis, and stiffness if not managed appropriately. Treatment usually involves a combination of surgical repair and reconstruction, followed by a carefully planned rehabilitation program.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The \u0027terrible triad\u0027 of the elbow consists of posterior elbow dislocation, radial head fracture, and coronoid process fracture.","Elbow dislocations are the second most common major joint dislocation in adults, after shoulder dislocations.","The \u0027terrible triad\u0027 injury is associated with significant instability and requires careful management to prevent complications."],"references":["Reichert IL, Ganeshamoorthy S, Aggarwal S, Arya A, Sinha J. Dislocations of the elbow - An instructional review. J Clin Orthop Trauma. 2021 Jul 13;21:101484. doi: 10.1016/j.jcot.2021.101484. Erratum in: J Clin Orthop Trauma. 2021 Jul 30;20:101539. doi: 10.1016/j.jcot.2021.101539. PMID: 34367909; PMCID: PMC8321949.","Ohl X, Siboni R. Surgical treatment of terrible triad of the elbow. Orthopaedics \u0026 Traumatology: Surgery \u0026 Research. 2021;107(1, Supplement):102784. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877056820303753"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40090"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13853"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20800"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","